# Usecase Layer Rule

This rule defines the standards and best practices for the usecase (application) layer in the project, following Clean Architecture principles.

description: Defines usecase layer responsibilities, interface/implementation patterns, naming conventions, dependency injection, and best practices for Clean Architecture.
globs:
alwaysApply: false

## Purpose
- Encapsulate application-specific business logic and workflows
- Orchestrate interactions between domain entities, repositories, and external services
- Serve as the main entry point for application logic (e.g., authentication, user registration, project management)
- Decouple domain logic from delivery (API, CLI, etc.) and infrastructure

## Structure
- Each usecase should be defined as an interface (e.g., `LoginUsecase`, `RegisterUserUsecase`)
- Provide a concrete implementation for each usecase (e.g., `loginUsecaseImpl`, `registerUserUsecaseImpl`)
- Use dependency injection to provide repositories, services, and other dependencies to usecases
- Group related usecases in the same package or file for clarity

## Naming Conventions
- Use `XxxUsecase` for interfaces (e.g., `LoginUsecase`)
- Use `NewXxxUsecase` for constructors
- Use `xxxUsecaseImpl` or simply `usecase` for concrete implementations

## Interface Example
```go
// LoginUsecase defines the login workflow.
type LoginUsecase interface {
    Login(ctx context.Context, cred authentication.Credential) (*authentication.Session, error)
}

// loginUsecaseImpl is the concrete implementation.
type loginUsecaseImpl struct {
    userRepo repository.UserRepository
    tokenGen token.TokenGenerator
}

func NewLoginUsecase(userRepo repository.UserRepository, tokenGen token.TokenGenerator) LoginUsecase {
    return &loginUsecaseImpl{userRepo: userRepo, tokenGen: tokenGen}
}
```

## Best Practices
- Keep usecase logic focused and cohesive; avoid mixing unrelated concerns
- Use dependency injection for all external dependencies (repositories, services, etc.)
- Return domain-meaningful errors, not infrastructure or storage errors
- Write unit tests for all usecases, using mocks for dependencies
- Document each usecase’s purpose and workflow
- Extend usecases by adding new interfaces/implementations as needed

